<div class="pagewrap">
        <div class="archive-banner" style="margin-bottom: 55px;">
        <div class="archive-banner-bg">
            <img src="/images/archivebanner.png" alt="" data-object-fit="cover" loading="lazy">
        </div>
        <div class="container-fluid">
            <div class="row offset-lg-1 offset-xl-2">
                <div class="col-12 col-lg-11 col-xl-9">
                    <div class="archive-banner-content">
                        <h1 class="archive-banner-content-title h1">Policy Making Standards</h1>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flexibleblocks">
    <section class="flexibleblocks-block __text __animate ">
        <div class="container-fluid">
            <div class="row __center">
                <div class="col-12 col-lg-8 col-xl-6">
                    <div class="usercontent">
                        <p>A number of public bodies have duties, under the policy making standards, to consider the impact of policy decisions on the Welsh language.</p>
<p>The intention is that organisations incorporate the wider vision of the Welsh Language Measure of ensuring that the Welsh language is part of the fabric of public life in Wales, in their decision-making processes. It is a way of ensuring that the Welsh language is included as a mainstream subject when public bodies decide how to carry their public responsibilities. </p>
<p>This page provides guidance on how to ensure that conscientious consideration is given to the impact of decisions on the Welsh language.</p>
<p>Further resources will be added to this page so please visit regularly.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>


    <div class="flexibleblocks-block __accordions ">
        <div class="container-fluid">
            <div class="row __center">
                <div class="col-12 col-lg-8 col-xl-6">
                    <h2 class="h4 accordions-heading __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">FAQs - Policy Making Standards: Consultation Documents</h2>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-1" aria-controls="accordion-panel-1" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>1.	What is a consultation document in the context of Welsh language standards?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-1" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-1" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>A document that asks a stakeholder to consider and respond to proposals in relation to a policy decision. </p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-2" aria-controls="accordion-panel-2" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>2.	What does “policy decision&quot; mean?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-2" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-2" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>The Welsh Language Standards Regulations define a "policy decision" as any decision a body makes about:</p>
<ul>
<li>exercising its functions</li>
<li>conducting its business</li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p>It's an incredibly broad definition, and it's not limited to written documents called "policies". Examples may include:</p>
<ul>
<li>content of legislation</li>
<li>exercise of statutory power
<ul>
<li>decision to sell a leisure centre</li>
<li>decision to close a hospital ward</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>policy statements
<ul>
<li>street name policy</li>
<li>social media policy</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>strategy or strategic plan
<ul>
<li>corporate plan</li>
<li>local development plan</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>internal structure
<ul>
<li>governance processes</li>
<li>office location</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-3" aria-controls="accordion-panel-3" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>3. 	What is the extent of the consideration that needs to be given to the effects of a policy decision on the Welsh language in consultation documents?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-3" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-3" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>A "conscientious effort"<a name="_ftnref1" href="#_ftn1"><span>[1]</span></a> must be made to consider the impact of the decision on the Welsh language. The threshold for “conscientious effort” depends on the circumstances and more must be done:</p>
<p>- in a sensitive or significant area in terms of the Welsh language</p>
<p>- as the number and/or impact of the possible effects on the Welsh language increases</p>
<p>- if there is a local policy or guideline (e.g. in the field of education or planning) requiring an assessment of possible effects on the Welsh language</p>
<p>It is more likely that a “conscientious effort” will be made if a wide range of impacts are considered.</p>
<p>It is not sufficient to include a series of factual, general statements about the Welsh language (e.g. number and % of Welsh speakers in the area, information about Welsh-medium schools, the body's expenditure on the Welsh language etc.). That is not equivalent to considering the possible effects of the specific decision in question on the Welsh language.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><a name="_ftn1" href="#_ftnref1"><span>[1]</span></a> Welsh Language Tribunal decision in the case of Neath Port Talbot Council v Welsh Language Commissioner</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-4" aria-controls="accordion-panel-4" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>4. 	What kind of impacts need to be considered in consultation documents?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-4" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-4" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>Three types of impact need to be considered:</p>
<p>-             Positive</p>
<p>-             Neutral</p>
<p>-             Adverse</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Direct</strong> and <strong>indirect</strong> effects on the Welsh language must also be considered (e.g. if a decision is made about English-medium education, it must be considered whether that will affect Welsh-medium education).</p>
<p>The types of factors that can be considered include</p>
<p>-             the number of Welsh speakers (in a specific area, sector or group)</p>
<p>-             use of Welsh language services</p>
<p>-             social use of the Welsh language</p>
<p>-             the economic and cultural infrastructure of Welsh speaking communities</p>
<p>-             opportunities to learn Welsh</p>
<p> </p>
<p><a href="/public-organisations/advice-and-support/policy-making-standards/list-of-factors-to-consider-when-assessing-the-impact-of-policy-decisions-on-the-welsh-language" title="List of factors to consider when assessing the impact of policy decisions on the Welsh language" data-anchor="#">Further examples of the factors that should be considered are available here.</a></p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-5" aria-controls="accordion-panel-5" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>5. 	Is asking questions to stakeholders in the consultation document sufficient?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-5" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-5" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>No. A consultation document must "consider" the impact of the proposals on the Welsh language. In order to do that, enough information must be included in the consultation document so that stakeholders can consider and respond intelligently to the proposals. It is not acceptable to transfer the burden of identifying the effects of the proposals on the Welsh language to stakeholders.</p>
<p>In addition, the consultation document must "seek the views" of stakeholders. That can be done by asking specific questions in the document that require a response.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-6" aria-controls="accordion-panel-6" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>6. 	Is including an impact assessment on the Welsh language in a consultation document sufficient?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-6" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-6" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>Yes. The assessment can be included in the body of the document or as an appendix to it. If including the assessment as an appendix, attention should be drawn to that fact.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-7" aria-controls="accordion-panel-7" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>7. 	Does the impact on the Welsh language have to be considered in consultation documents if the policy decision is being formulated?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-7" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-7" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>Yes. It is not possible to postpone the consideration given to the potential impact of proposals on the Welsh language until the end of the consultation period. That would be contrary to the purpose of these standards which require it to be taken into account at the start of the consultation process.</p>
<p>It is possible that the consultation will highlight effects that the body has not thought about the start of the consultation process, and those effects should be considered as the process of making the decision goes on, but that does not exclude the body from giving conscientious consideration at the start of the process.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-8" aria-controls="accordion-panel-8" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>8. 	 Is a consultation report published at the end of the process considered part of the consultation document?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-8" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-8" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>No it isn't. A 'consultation document' and a 'consultation report' are two separate documents. The purpose of the standards is to ensure that appropriate consideration is given to the Welsh language while the proposals are in a formative phase. A 'consultation report' is a document that is created after the consultation process has ended, and where decisions are taken, and is therefore not relevant to these standards.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-9" aria-controls="accordion-panel-9" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>9.	Do these standards apply to other ways of engaging with stakeholders?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-9" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-9" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>These standards relate to the publication of a consultation document and not to other methods of consultation or engagement such as public meetings, face-to-face interviews, call-in sessions etc. However, if documents are shared at events like this that require a stakeholder to consider and respond to policy proposals, then these standards apply to those documents.</p>
<p>In addition, mainstreaming the Welsh language into other consultation or engagement exercises is good practice, and will help organisations to comply with other policy making standards.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="accordion Accordion __animatefade __stagger1 __animatein">
                                <button class="accordion-head AccordionTrigger" id="accordion-button-10" aria-controls="accordion-panel-10" aria-expanded="false">
                                    <span>10. 	Where can I find further guidance?</span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion-content AccordionContent" id="accordion-panel-10" aria-labelledby="accordion-button-10" aria-hidden="true" style="display: none;">
                                    <div class="usercontent">
                                        <p>Further guidance is available by following the links below:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.welshlanguagecommissioner.wales/media/hgqdctio/code-of-practice-regulations-1.pdf">Code of Practice for the Welsh Language Standards Regulations (No. 1) 2015</a><a name="_ftnref1" href="#_ftn1"><span>[1]</span></a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.welshlanguagecommissioner.wales/media/tvunlads/20200921-dg-s-policy-making-standards-final.pdf">Policy making standards - good practice advice document</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c-RTTxBibYo">Consultation documents seminar</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ImHQSCyU_h8&amp;feature=youtu.be">Policy making standards seminar</a></li>
<li><a href="https://tribiwnlysygymraeg.llyw.cymru/sites/welshlanguage/files/2023-10/penderfyniad-nptcbc-0923.pdf">Judgment of the Welsh Language Tribunal: Neath Port Talbot Council v Welsh Language Commissioner</a></li>
<li><a href="https://tribiwnlysygymraeg.llyw.cymru/sites/welshlanguage/files/2022-07/penderfyniad-achos-tyg2101-27-07-2022.pdf">Welsh Language Tribunal Judgment: Swansea Council v Welsh Language Commissioner</a></li>
</ul>
<p> </p>
<p><a name="_ftn1" href="#_ftnref1"><span>[1]</span></a> No code of practice for other sets of Welsh language standards regulations have been published yet, but the content of this code is relevant to other bodies that are subject to the same duty in other regulations.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

